[2] Brazil (Amazon)
Date: Fri 6 Jul 2018
Source: ProMED-ESP article title translations - Vol 8, Issue 169 [edited]
https://excelsior.com.mx/global/muere-bebe-de-siete-meses-por-sarampion-confirman-que-no-fue-vacunado/1250555


Brazilian authorities confirmed today [6 Jul 2018] that a 7 month old baby had died of measles in the city of Manaus, capital of the state of Amazonas (north), so that the number of victims of this disease has risen to 3 in recent months. The baby, who had not been vaccinated, died on 28 Jun 2018, but the causes were confirmed Thu [6 Jul 2018] by the Ministry of Health of Manaus, a city that has decreed a state of emergency after a new outbreak of measles.

Only in Manaus, 270 cases of this infectious disease caused by morbillivirus have been confirmed since March 2018, particularly among children.

The increase in suspected cases increases the possibility of dissemination to other states of the country and puts at risk the commitments for the maintenance of the certificate of elimination of the measles virus in the regions of the Americas, notes the secretariat.

In addition to Amazonas, the state of Roraima -- also in the northern region of the country -- has recorded 2 measles deaths in recent months.

In 2017, measles cases rose by 400 per cent in Europe. Last February 2018, WHO warned of the rise of measles in Europe in 2017, with 35 deaths and 21 315 cases, 400 per cent more than in 2016, when a historical minimum was reported with 5273 cases. A total of 15 of the 53 countries that make up the European region of the WHO suffered a "big outbreak" of measles in the last year, with Romania heading the list with 5562 cases, followed by Italy with 5006 and Ukraine with 4767 cases.

After these 3 countries, the others that experienced outbreaks were Greece (927 cases), Germany (927), Serbia (702), Tajikistan (649), France (520), Russia (408), Belgium (369), United Kingdom (282), Bulgaria (167), Spain (152), Czech Republic (146) and Switzerland (105), although many of them were decreasing at the end of 2017.

"More than 20 000 cases of measles and 35 lives lost in 2017 alone is a tragedy that we simply cannot accept," said WHO regional director for Europe Zsuzsanna Jakab in a statement published in the framework of the ministerial meeting on health about immunization held in Montenegro. "Every new person affected by measles in Europe reminds us that unvaccinated children and adults, regardless of where they live, are still at risk of contracting the disease and spreading it to others who may not be able to get vaccinated," she added.

